-- U.S.-based stock funds attract $4.2 bln over week - Lipper
-- By Sam Forgione
-- Thu May 01, 2014 04:57PM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, May 1 (Reuters) - Investors in U.S.-based funds poured $4.2 billion into stock funds in the week ended Wednesday, marking the biggest inflows into the funds in three weeks, data from Thomson Reuters' Lipper service showed on Thursday.

Stock mutual funds attracted $1.6 billion of the net inflows, while stock exchange-traded funds attracted $2.6 billion. Emerging markets stock funds attracted $352 million in inflows, marking their sixth straight week of inflows.  Taxable bond funds attracted $711 million in new cash, marking their smallest inflows in eight weeks. High-yield bond funds posted $631 million in outflows, marking their biggest outflows since February. Floating-rate loan funds posted $663.7 million in outflows, marking their biggest outflows since August 2011, while corporate investment-grade bond funds posted $74 million in outflows, marking their first withdrawals since October 2013. Money market funds posted $5.5 billion in outflows after attracting $4.9 billion in inflows the previous week.